<LEADPARA>  Commissioner Fay Vincent on Monday presented a grim scenario of baseball's
financial health, disclosing for the first time that at least eight teams had
not been profitable in 1990.;    Vincent, returning to his office after an
81-day absence caused by health problems, implied that escalating salaries
threaten baseball. He likened them to the junk-bond market of the 1980s.
"Things that look like they make no sense, make no sense," he said.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THERE'S TROUBLE, BASEBALL INSISTS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See related article this page  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     To underscore his point, Vincent said that at least 10 and possibly as many
as 12 teams can be characterized as having "serious problems." Although he did
not name them, the teams are believed to include the Pittsburgh Pirates, the
Seattle Mariners, the Houston Astros and the Milwaukee Brewers.;    The
Mariners, Vincent pointed out, expect that their total revenues for the coming
season will not match the payroll of the Boston Red Sox.;    Vincent said
"it's hard to convince people there are financial problems," given the huge TV
contracts baseball signed last year and the four-year, $21 million contract
that the Red Sox gave pitcher Roger Clemens last week.;    One person hard to
convince is Donald Fehr, executive director of the Major League Players
Association.;    Asked whether a lot of clubs lost money last season, Fehr
said: "I have no way of knowing if the commissioner's definition of losing
money is the same as mine. For example, the Pirates' losses are all
attributable to their payment of collusion damages. To that extent, they can
claim they lost money, but they're writing off four or five years of expenses
in one year.";    Asked about the commissioner's assertion of "financial
problems," Fehr said, "This kind of advance predicting for the sake of
predicting is curious, given their apparent lack of concern as they negotiate
salaries this winter.";    Economic analysis;    Economists interviewed by the
Associated Press also said big contracts can be justified.;    "It wouldn't
surprise me if $5 million is not unreasonable for Roger Clemens," said Lou
Guth, senior vice president of National Economic Research Associates and a
former economic consultant for baseball's Player Relations Committee. "The
problem isn't with Roger Clemens. The problem is with the middle guys, the $2
million guys with minimal, marginal contributions.";    Asher Blass, a senior
economist with Lexicon Corp., also says the Clemens deal might make sense from
an economic standpoint. "He might pay his way," Blass said. "With the national
and local TV revenue and if they draw 2 1/2 million a year with concessions,
the possible gross is $40 million.";    Blass' doctoral dissertation at
Harvard dealt with the economics of major league baseball.;    "The money is
being spent," he said. "If these salaries were uneconomical, you'd observe
team prices going down. The new franchises are priced at $95 million, and
there are no shortage of takers at that price.;    "It suggests the industry
remains profitable.";    Pirates' problems;  In Pittsburgh, Pirates President
Carl Barger said he is resigned to losing some of the club's marquee players
in the next two years.;    "We can't afford to keep them all," Barger said.;
 Barger made his remarks after outfielder/infielder Bobby Bonilla rejected the
Pirates' four-year, $15.5 million offer. Bonilla, who is asking for nearly $20
million, has threatened to play elsewhere if the Pirates don't sign him to a
long-term deal before his arbitration hearing Thursday.;    The unprecedented
salary escalation over the last five years "keeps going from one plateau to
another . . . and it puts you in a position where you can't keep all of your
home-grown players," Barger said. "Each time we have a further spiraling, I
say it's got to be the end, then there's a signing like Clemens.";    Barger
called Boston's contract with Clemens "irresponsible.";    "It's another
classic example of how ownership is tearing the heart out of baseball for no
good reason," he said. "It was a double-barrel shock . . . the timing -- the
Friday before arbitration -- was incredible, and (the contract) beyond my
wildest imagination. I don't know whether to be angry or depressed.;    "One
of the things that worries me -- even more than the effect of the recession on
baseball -- is that baseball fans will just get sick and tired of hearing
about the economics and get turned off," he said.  </TEXT>
