<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- On Sports: Pittsburgh Pirates: The Young and Hungry </HL>
<AUTHOR> Frederick C. Klein </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<DATELINE> Bradenton, Fla.  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It rained hard Saturday night along the Gulf Coast, and on Sunday morning the infield at McKechnie Field here was so wet that grounds crewmen were using plastic bottles to scoop up the standing water.
Yet even a soggy baseball diamond looked good to this refugee from Calgary and other points north.
Wet grass beats dry ice anytime.

   The prospect of a ball game also was welcome to the Pittsburgh Pirates, who make their spring home at ancient McKechnie.
They were anxious to open their Grapefruit League schedule Sunday afternoon against the Texas Rangers.
"Oh, yeah, we're ready," said Andy Van Slyke, the Pittsburgh centerfielder.
"Last year we came into spring training on a catamaran.
This time we got a battleship."

   The Bucs are still souped up by their good showing of late last season, when they won 27 of their final 38 games.
The surge put their full-season record at 80-82, good for fourth place in the National League East.
That might not have been braggable in some precincts, but fourth was the highest the team had finished since 1983, and it followed three straight years in sixth, or last, place.
Moreover, its 16-win gain over 1986 matched St. Louis in the Majors' "most-improved" category.

   Making the showing all the more impressive was the fact that the Pirates employed 49 different players in 105 different starting lineups during the campaign, challenging the New York Yankees' longtime hold on baseball's Team Turnover title.
"Things were so unsettled they were putting names on guys' uniforms with Velcro instead of sewing them on," said quipster Van Slyke.

   General Manager Syd Thrift engineered last season's shuffle, and while he does not rule out further moves, he implies they will be retail rather than wholesale.
"We now have a respectable team," he declares.

   The aptly named Thrift also has an economical team, because many of the 1987 departers were high-priced veterans.
The usual reasoning in these cases is that it is cheaper to lose with a young team than with an old one.
Traded away during the season were such vets as catcher Tony Pena (to St. Louis), pitchers Rick Reuschel and Don Robinson (both to San Francisco), shortstop Bill Almon (to the New York Mets), third baseman Jim Morrison (to Detroit) and second baseman Johnny Ray (to California).
Some of those guys could even play.

   But so, too, could some of the fellas Thrift acquired.
Probably his best deal was an April 1 one that brought in Van Slyke, pitcher Mike Dunne and catcher Mike LaValliere from the Cardinals for Pena.
Van Slyke, a lamppost in St. Louis, became a candidate for mayor of Pittsburgh by batting .293 with 22 home runs and 82 runs batted in.
LaValliere hit .300 and won a Golden Glove award.
Dunne led the Bucs' starting pitchers with 13 wins and a 3.03 earned run average.
The Cardinals won the pennant with Pena, but why be selfish?

   Other key Pirate pickups were relief pitchers Jeff Robinson, who came in the Reuschel trade, and Jim Gott, purchased for the $50,000 waiver price from Toronto.
Both arrived in August and gave the team the relief pitching it previously lacked.
The strapping Gott had 13 saves in 16 opportunities, and permitted just two earned runs in his last 27 innings.

   Home-grown left fielder Barry Bonds, Bobby's son, hit 25 home runs and stole 32 bases in his second big league season.
Second baseman Jose Lind did well enough in the minors to allow Ray to be traded, and hit .322 for Pittsburgh in 35 games.
Doug Drabek and Brian Fisher, acquired from the Yankees in 1986, started a total of 54 games and won 22.
None is older than 26.

   Indeed, except for 31-year-old pitcher Bob Walk, the Bucs could open the season without a player over 30.
That's OK with manager Jim Leyland as long as it doesn't become the season's focus.
"When you're as young as we are, it's tempting to look at the future instead of the here-now," he says.
"You improve by getting better today, not tomorrow.
That's what we'll be stressing and looking for."

   Leyland this spring will look particularly hard at his infield, which is untried except for first baseman Sid Bream.
Rookie Lind is at second base, rookie Felix Fermin and second-year-man Al Pedrique will vie for the shortstop job, and Bobby Bonilla, who last year proved he could hit (15 homers, 77 RBIs), is being moved to third base from first and the outfield.
The husky Bonilla is considered a question mark afield by some, but not himself.
"Playing third is just like playing first, except for the throw," he says blithely.

   Pitching, of course, is 81.3% of baseball, and Pittsburgh's is in the heretofore capable hands of coach Ray Miller.
He earned distinction in that post for a couple of American League pennant winners at Baltimore, so it is noteworthy that he believes his Pirate crew is potentially as able as his old Orioles flock.
"We've got 10-12 guys who can throw 90 miles an hour," he says.
"There ought to be a decent staff in there somewhere."

   Miller believes that pitching is more craft than gift, and hastens to note that this accent on velocity doesn't mean he has strayed from his mound dictum of "work fast, change speeds and throw strikes."
He avers that "all the speed in the world won't make a guy a winner if that's all he's got."
Yet he adds: "It's easier to change speeds when you can throw 90 than 80.
More effective, too."

   That this could be a brighter year for Pittsburgh was suggested in Sunday's spring opener.
Not only did the rain refrain, but the Bucs prevailed, 6-1, breaking a 1-1 tie in the eighth inning with a string of five hits and a walk.
Manager Leyland was pleased, but, this being spring, restrained in his elation.

   "Two bad things can happen after a season like we had last year: The kids can believe the people who say they've got it made, or the ones who say their improvement was a fluke," he said.
"I'd just as soon they forgot the evaluations for now, and read the funnies instead."

</TEXT>
