<DESCRIPT>  EDITORIAL; PROFESSIONAL; BASEBALL  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  SO THE poor, working class Pittsburgh Pirates couldn't match the $29 million
contract the filthy rich New York Mets just gave to baseball slugger Bobby
Bonilla. That's the line from baseball owners and players who love to say the
national pastime operates in "free enterprise.";   In this thinking, the rich
teams in big markets get better by outbidding the small-market teams for
superstar players. This mythology is denser than Babe Ruth's potbelly.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FANS GET THE SHORT END OF THE BAT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Editorials; A Personal View; Joseph Rodriguez is a Mercury News editorial
writer.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     First, it doesn't explain why two teams from the smallest markets,
Minnesota and Atlanta, were in the World Series and the California Angels were
not and never have been despite spending a mint on superstars.;   The truth is
that major league baseball is a monopoly that earns much of its income from a
regulated, semi-monopoly -- the three television networks. Most teams play in
stadiums subsidized by taxpayers.;   To preserve the league and monopoly,
baseball teams need to protect the weakest teams from going broke, which means
cooperating in ways that would normally violate anti-trust laws. The amateur
draft is an example. Imagine all the hospitals in America taking turns
selecting medical school graduates, giving them no alternatives.;   Baseball's
monopoly used to be ironclad until the courts freed players from the grips of
owners. But all that really changed was that player salaries shot through the
roof, Bonilla's being only the latest.;   We could talk all we want about
owner-player agreements to cap salaries, but that, too, would be monopolistic.
It's futile to try to curb the high bidding, especially when owners are either
too dumb or rich to care.;   The real crime of baseball's monopoly is that too
many cities that can support major league baseball are shut out. They have to
root for minor league teams that exist merely to teach rookie pitchers how to
throw curveballs.;   There is no sound economic reason why the growing Phoenix
market (pop. 2.1 million) can't have a team when the Kansas City market (pop.
1.5 million) does. With a population of 18 million, the New York area could
support four teams, not just two. The Bay Area (pop. 6.2 million and two
teams) could support another in San Jose.;   Expecting the leagues and their
allies in Congress to break the monopoly is a dream. The best American
baseball fans can hope for is true expansion. I mean doubling or tripling the
number of teams, not just two new admissions once a decade.;   Even if big
stadiums are half filled, so what? The optimum stadium capacity for excellent
baseball viewing is about 35,000. Big Shea Stadium in New York doesn't inspire
poetry. But Fenway Park in Boston does. Who benefits from gigantic stadiums
with lousy views? Owners and superstars, that's who.;   True major league
expansion would bring smaller stadiums, better seats and lower prices to
happier fans and taxpayers.  </TEXT>
