<DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; BASEBALL; PRESIDENT; PITTSBURGH; RESIGN; UNUSUAL  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Carl Barger resigned Monday as the Pittsburgh Pirates' president to take the
same position with the expansion Florida Marlins. Under a unique arrangement,
however, Barger will virtually run both teams indefinitely.;    Baseball's
conflict-of-interest rules bar a major league club employee from working for
another team, but Barger will begin staffing the Marlins' front office while
running the Pirates until his successor is chosen.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  PIRATES' BARGER HIRED TO RUN FLORIDA MARLINS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Baseball Notebook  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Barger could remain in Pittsburgh until the end of the season even while
selecting key executives -- including a general manager and manager -- for the
Marlins.;    "Sure, you can create some sort of spectrum of conflict, but if
you do, you don't know me," Barger said. "I'll be happy to pass any oversight
test anyone wants to give me. . . . I'll devote 120 percent of my energies to
the Pirates as long as I'm here. I bleed black and gold.";    Barger's new
colors will be aqua and orange, which his close friend, H. Wayne Huizenga, the
Marlins' millionaire owner, chose for his new franchise. The Marlins will join
the National League with the Denver-based Colorado Rockies in 1993.;
Huizenga also didn't see any conflict of interest in Barger working for both
the Pirates and Marlins.;    "We don't have a club to run," Huizenga said.
"For Carl to spend a few more months with the team he helped build and
considers his baby, I see nothing wrong with that.";    Huizenga said Barger
will consult with him on decisions about the Marlins but will have "complete
authority" to run the team. Huizenga said he hopes to hire a general manager
in the next four months.;    Pirates Chairman Douglas Danforth, who also
chaired the N.L. expansion committee, said Commissioner Fay Vincent agreed
Barger could remain with the Pirates for the near future.;    "Based on what
Carl has done in the past, I have every confidence he will be able to handle
the responsibilities of both positions," Vincent said. "I can see how the
(conflict of interest) subject would come up. I'm not naive. But there is
nothing to that. I would think his duties with the Pirates would not last
long.";    Danforth said he would like Barger to remain with the Pirates
primarily to help negotiate a complicated stadium-lease agreement with the
city.;    Barger said he won't stockpile the Marlins' front office with
current Pirates executives.;    "There is an anti-tampering rule in baseball
which the expansion franchises are subject to," Barger said. "Beyond that, I
have a track record of 30 years of honesty and integrity. I would no more raid
or hurt this organization for the betterment of another organization than I
would fly to the moon.";  PALERMO UPDATE: American League umpire Steve Palermo
was improving and doctors upgraded his condition from serious to fair one day
after he was shot while trying to aid two robbery victims in Dallas.;    "We
still don't know much about his recovery time," American League President
Bobby Brown said. "We hope it will be brief.";  ETC.: Doctors have determined
that Milwaukee Brewers center fielder Robin Yount's recent health problem
resulted from a passed kidney stone. The Brewers said Yount might return to
the lineup Thursday. . . . Montreal pitcher Dennis "Oil Can" Boyd, who will
become a free agent after this season, has asked the Expos to either sign him
to a new contract or trade him. . . . Seattle Mariners second baseman Harold
Reynolds was named the recipient of the Roberto Clemente award for his
outstanding service to the community. . . . National League President Bill
White has urged the Rockies' owners to hire a minority in a high-profile
front-office position, the Rocky Mountain News reported. . . . New York Mets
first baseman Dave Magadan is suffering from a small cartilage tear in his
right shoulder and will require off-season arthroscopic surgery.  </TEXT>
