<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- On Sports:
   Boos for the Pirates' `Killer B's'
   ----
   By Frederick C. Klein
</HL>
<DATE>
04/10/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A20
</SO>
<LP>
   Pittsburgh -- You know you are in Pittsburgh when you get
in a cab at the airport, tell the driver to take you to a
local installation of a national hotel chain and he asks,
"You mean the one donton?"
   You also knew you were in Pittsburgh when, on Monday's
opening night for the National League East champion Pirates,
many in attendance at Three Rivers Stadium greeted the
introduction of the home team's slugging "Killer B's" --
Barry Bonds and Bobby Bonilla -- with another "B" word,
"Boo]"
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Bonds, winner of the league's most-valuable-player award
last year, distinguished himself in the off-season by being
awarded a 1991 salary of $2.4 million while losing an
arbitration battle with the team. His subsequent muttering
culminated in a spring-training shouting match with manager
Jim Leyland, during which Leyland was heard to say that if he
ran the team to suit Bonds, his "butt would be managing a
7-Eleven store somewhere," and soon.
   Bonilla finished second to Bonds in the MVP voting. His
losing arbitration case netted him $2.3 mil. The team then
reportedly offered him a four-year, $16 million deal, but he
refused it and his agent characterized later Pirate
bargaining bids as "grandstanding." Bonilla says he'll
probably be a free agent after this campaign, and trade
rumors involving him abound.
   At a time when the average Major League player's salary
exceeds $800,000, and baseball fans discuss paychecks as
readily as prospects, no team rattled the teller's cage
louder than the Pirates in the time twixt the seasons. Doug
Drabek, the team's pitching ace, won a record arbitration
award of $3.4 million. Andy Van Slyke, Bond's and Bonilla's
outfield mate, just signed a three-year pact, effective next
year, worth $12.6 million, the game's fourth-largest on an
annual basis. Pitcher Chuck Heaton, who is making a modest
$1.1 million, raised some eyebrows by remarking that in
today's climate a $600,000 annual salary amounts to
"dogmeat."
   Pirate management, meantime, bemoaned its city's
"small-market" status and allowed that, at those rates,
winning might have become more than it could afford.
   To say that the local burghers swallowed that talk like so
much Rolling Rock would be an overstatement. "There's a
recession on, and here you have people {the players} making
millions {of dollars, of course} and complaining about it.
It's sickening," said Scott Davidson, a roofer from New
Brighton, Pa.
   "Management let a good guy like {first baseman} Sid Bream
go {to Atlanta, via free agency} but they gave the
complainers millions {bucks again}. Where's the justice in
that?" asked Kate Rau, a technical writer from Allison Park.
   It's worth noting, however, that Mr. Davidson and Ms. Rau
were doing their grousing at Three Rivers Stadium, after
having paid to watch the Pirates open against the Montreal
Expos. That is the curious thing about fan reaction to the
salary boom: The more they moan, the more they go to the
ballpark. In 1989, the Major Leagues drew a record 55.2
million people during regular-season action, and last year's
figure fell just 350,000 short of that despite an owners'
lockout that delayed opening day.
   As was reported in this newspaper Monday, every year it
costs more to attend a game than it did the year before; Team
Marketing Report, a sports newsletter, put this season's
day-at-the-park tab for a Typical Family of Four at $76.22,
up 9% from 1990 (although I thought the kids might have done
without those two, $7.85 baseball caps). The newsletter did
not mention anyone having to put a gun to the head of the
household chief to force that expenditure.
   And, indeed, last year, when player salaries also were too
high, the Pirates drew a record 2,049,908 people, and
reserved-seat price increases of $1 or 50-cents here this
year didn't halt a boost in season-ticket sales to 15,000
from 11,000, which alone works out to about 320,000 more
fannies in the seats seasonlong.
   "It is American to complain about money. It is also
American to sit in a ballpark on a sunny day watching the
geometrically perfect game of baseball," declared Pirate fan
Bill Gerstner, an oil-company purchasing agent from Butler.
"I see no conflict in doing both."
   Neither did others who paid to show up on an unseasonably
warm evening in a number -- 54,247 -- that set a Pirate
single-game record for the 105-year-old franchise. Recurrent
episodes of misty rain did not disturb them noticeably, and
while a 7-0 Montreal victory, on a one-hit pitching effort by
veterans Dennis Martinez and Barry Jones, wasn't what they
came to see, it sufficed.
   Apparently voting that he ought to be managing the Bucs
instead of a 7-Eleven, the fans gave manager Leyland a
standing "O" at intro time, and showed that they weren't
totally Bond-proof by cheering that fella when -- what else?
-- his line-drive, seventh-inning single spoiled Martinez's
no-hitter.
   Afterward, in the sanctity of their locker room, the
Pirates gave every indication that they were glad to see the
preseason end and the season begin. The loss, said Leyland
after tipping his cap to Martinez's pitching acumen, was "one
game of 162. I really like this team, and one loss won't
change that."
   Across the way, Bond interrupted his postgame meal to
voice much the same sentiment. "It's just one game," he
noted. "We'll be back tomorrow."
   Bonilla is, generally, a type whose face forms smiles more
easily than frowns, and he allowed that he found the
commencement of hostilities especially welcome. "You put
other things aside when the season starts," he said quietly.
But to a television reporter's question about "the mood in
the clubhouse," he looked aghast.
   "The mood in the clubhouse?]" he exclaimed. "This is just
day one]"
   But he added: "Look around. Ain't nobody throwing stuff.
That must mean the mood is good."
</TEXT>
