<HL>
   Business World:
   Second-Tier City May Be First to Put Taxpayers in Play
   ----
   By Tim W. Ferguson
</HL>
<DATE>
10/01/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A21
</SO>
<MS>
CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)
</MS>
<IN>
ENTERTAINMENT AND LEISURE (ENT)
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY (REC)
</IN>
<RE>
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
PACIFIC RIM (PRM)
UNITED STATES (US)
WASHINGTON (WA)
</RE>
<LP>
   The pennant race in the American League's Western division
is over, but the drama continues around the cellar-flirting
Seattle Mariners baseball team.
   Actually, the strength of the division makes that standing
misleading: The Mariners are having their best year ever on
the field. It's the cash register that's the problem: not so
much the attendance, which at two million is double the
team's average prior to last year, but the other moneymakers
in modern sports -- television contracts, advertising, luxury
boxes.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mariners majority owner Jeff Smulyan, a radio
entrepreneur, blames the Seattle business community for not
backing him up on his big play. Two years after taking over
the team, there's worry he'll use an escape clause in his
lease at the local Kingdome after 1992.
   With player costs mushrooming, Mr. Smulyan projects losing
a total of $20 million this season and next. Not only does he
want the locals to cover the gap, but he says he'll need an
additional $7 million annually to manage a "competitive"
effort. The invoice is due this fall, he says.
   The city is sensitive to owner infidelity because it was
jilted once before, in 1970, when after only one year a
franchise called the Pilots moved to Milwaukee to become the
Brewers. Seattle sued Major League Baseball and forced the
placement of a new team there in 1977. Shortly after the
premiere, however, the town decided it had better things to
do.
   The Mariners were taking so many bad hops by 1985 that
local officials offered better terms. Those concessions will
amount to $28 million by 1996, according to one unsympathetic
politician. This is the sort of stuff (kickbacks from food
and beverages, parking) that sports moguls typically are able
to wangle from local government -- in addition to the
building of bold stadiums like the indoor Kingdome, of
course.
   But Mr. Smulyan is going a bit further. He wants the dough
delivered to the front door. The home county obliged by
helping to buy up empty seats for remaining dates this
season. Other ideas have government making payments on a
Mariner bank loan, or acquiring a stake. Some people believe
the value of sports franchises will continue to rise come
fair winds or foul, and therefore presume a capital gain for
the taxpayers from ownership.
   Seattle wouldn't be the first town to pay up front for the
pleasure of a team's company. In 1985, Pittsburgh floated a
$20 million bond to assist a group buying the Pirates. The
resulting interest-free "equity participation loan" looks a
lot like stock, as no repayment is due until sale of the
team. Montreal just did a sweetheart loan for the Expos. But
actual municipal equity would be unique for big-time pro
sports, if you don't count a community corporation that holds
football's Green Bay Packers.
   Whatever form public assistance took in Seattle, it would
amount to one more drain on taxpayers. Some say fine. Slade
Gorton, a Republican U.S. senator from Washington (and the
man who, as state attorney general, sued to get the Mariner
franchise), drew an interesting parallel in a recent Rotary
speech: "In a way, major-league baseball contributes to the
community in a manner similar to that of the city's art and
cultural establishmentand is almost as unlikely to show an
annual net profit in monetary terms."
   Further, whatever the authorities come up with is likely
to be more than matched by the local businesses that are
roped into the "partnership." But corporate expenditures
usually lead to tax write-offs (advertising, entertainment),
so even that will reflect on public policy.
   Seattle's is just one of many strapped franchises chasing
the rich teams around the budgetary base paths. The M's
revenues are at the bottom end and about 40% of those of the
New York Yankees, for example. Television contracts are the
big difference, and it's going to take a lot of Public
$piritedness to keep pace with the Big Apple bucks.
   Meanwhile, the ante in this game goes up and up. Areas
outbid each other in erecting playing palaces. (Tampa-St.
Petersburg even put one up in the mere anticipation of a
team; it now woos the Mariners.) And one public-sector plunge
isn't the end of it: Witness the fact the Pittsburgh
operation is still shaky, even as it has won two straight
division titles.
   The Pirates' experience belies the notion that making the
Mariners "competitive" will get them over the long-run
financial hump. Indeed, tapping the tax till in places such
as Seattle may simply allow the fat cats of Major League
Baseball to put off an obvious reform such as sharing local
broadcast revenues with their less-blessed brethren in this
Congress-approved trust.
   Even without some great equalizer, Seattle-sized cities
can take heart from evidence that a big population base no
more predicts success on the field than winning ensures
financial soundness. This bit of unorthodoxy comes from
Michael Canes, an economist with the American Petroleum
Institute. As a baseball fan, Mr. Canes naturally loves
statistics. For a recent academic paper, he examined who has
won and lost since baseball's last big expansion in 1969
(omitting the Mariners and Toronto's Blue Jays, both born
later).
   He found that the five American League teams with the most
winning seasons were, in order: Boston, Baltimore, New York,
Detroit and Kansas City. Baltimore and Kansas City are lesser
markets. In the National League, the top five were Los
Angeles, Cincinnati, Pittsburgh, New York and St. Louis --
only two were top-tier cities.
   The biggest losers in the American were Cleveland (a
runaway last), Chicago and California (LA/Orange County). In
the National, it was San Diego, Atlanta and Chicago. Half are
in larger markets.
   Mr. Canes conceded that "team expenditures are positively
related to winning. But "city size has little influence on
winning." His suspicion is that a good front office, one that
picks the right players and makes it pleasant to come to the
ballpark, matters most.
   Which brings us back to Mr. Smulyan. Maybe he's done all
he can in a town that loves "caffe latte" more than Cracker
Jack and has fewer kids per capita than anyplace outside of
San Francisco (hence, less demand for autographs, souvenirs
and foot-long hot dogs). Certainly others did worse before
him.
   In that case, if baseball is going to be Darwinian within
its 28-team universe, it might be best simply to have
franchises routinely die off. In reaction to the Canes paper,
one academic suggested emulating European soccer and
regularly booting out the worst two squads, in favor of the
best pair from the minors. (I can hear the cheers all the way
from Buffalo.)
   That might not finish the Mariners after this year's .500
season, but it would be curtains for Cleveland (sorry about
that new stadium, folks). Some high-priced jocks would have
to change addresses sooner than usual, but as it is they seem
to stay in one uniform only long enough to collect on
appliance endorsements and be hauled into court for divorce
or drunkenness.
   Better shut up now, cynic, you're headed for extra
innings. See, you needn't be second-tier to get an attitude.
Try following the Angels in Dodgertown.
</TEXT>
