<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- On Sports: Another Remarkable Season </HL>
<AUTHOR> Frederick C. Klein </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<TEXT>
   What kind of a baseball season was it?
A remarkable one, of course.
They all are.

   It was the year of the balk: 924 of them were called in the Major Leagues, an all-time and, one hopes, evermore record.
But the pitchers didn't squawk too much, because it also was the year they let the air out of the baseball: The 3,180 home runs hit in both leagues was down 29% from 1987.

   For the third consecutive season, no divisional winner repeated; only the Kansas City Royals (1984-85) have managed the trick since the strike-split 1981 campaign.
The Baltimore Orioles opened their season with 21 straight losses; the California Angels closed theirs by losing 12 in a row.

   Jose Canseco, the Oakland A's strong boy, became the first big leaguer to hit 40 home runs and steal 40 bases in a season, and was promptly compared with Ben Johnson.
A $6 million palimony suit didn't keep Boston's Wade Boggs from leading all hitters with a .366 average.
The Chicago Cubs, always remarkable, led the National League in team batting at .261, but were out-hit by their opponents.

   It was a remarkable season in other ways, too.
Here are some examples.

   Most-Remarkable Performance by a Hitter -- San Diego relief pitcher Dave Leiper singled in a run in the 16th inning of a game at Atlanta on Aug. 8.
It was his first time at bat in a seven-year professional career.

   Most-Remarkable Performance by Two Teams of Hitters -- The Colorado Springs Sky Sox and Phoenix Firebirds hit a Pacific Coast League record 13 home runs in a May 7 game at the Sox' mile-plus-high stadium in 40-mph winds.
Former Major-Leaguer Ed Lynch, making his first start for Phoenix, gave up five homers in four innings in a 33-12 defeat.
He retired from baseball the next day.

   Most-Remarkable Fielding Performance -- In the fourth inning of a July 27 home game against Milwaukee, New York Yankee pitcher Tommy John bobbled a roller by Jeffrey Leonard and threw wild past first base.
As Jim Gantner, on base ahead of Leonard, tried to score, John cut off Dave Winfield's throw from the outfield and heaved the ball into the Brewers' dugout.
Told later that he'd tied the Major League record for pitchers by making three errors on one play, held by J. Bentley Seymour of the 1898 New York Giants, the 45-year-old John quipped, "I think I pitched against him in the Eastern League."

   Most-Remarkable Performance by a Pitcher -- Bud Black of the Cleveland Indians hit three of the four batters he faced in the fourth inning of a July 8 game against the Angels at Anaheim.

   Most-Remarkable Pitching Matchups -- May 14 at Houston: Nipper (Chicago) vs.
Knepper (Astros).
June 19 at Chicago: Filer (Milwaukee) vs.
LaPoint (White Sox).
Aug. 23 at Pittsburgh: Browning (Cincinnati) vs.
Dunne (Pirates).

   Most-Remarkable Expenditure -- The Minnesota Twins spent $23,000 for a machine that removes tobacco-juice stains from its artificial-turf field.

   Most-Remarkable Explanation -- "Some players didn't recognize that different behavior is required on a commercial flight than on a charter," said Jim Ferguson, publicity director for the Cincinnati Reds, after team members grabbed stewardesses and threw food on an April 13 Continental Airlines flight to Houston from San Francisco.

   Most-Remarkable Parking Ticket -- Cincinnati manager Pete Rose was tagged for illegal parking on a street near the Reds' ballpark.
The street was Pete Rose Way.

   Most-Remarkable Injury -- Angels outfielder Chili Davis dislocated a toe when he kicked a chair after popping out in a June 26 home game against Milwaukee.
He'd first whacked a punching bag installed by manager Cookie Rojas to allow players to relieve their frustrations, but said he didn't punch it again "because I almost broke my wrist the first time."

   Most-Remarkable Scheduling Change -- Atlanta Braves management moved an Aug. 25 game against Chicago to 5:45 p.m. from 7:35 so cable station WTBS, also owned by team owner Ted Turner, could show a colorized version of the movie "Dr.
Jekyll and Mr. Hyde" in prime time.

   Most-Remarkable Performance by an Umpire -- Brian Owen, working a Texas League game at El Paso between the home Diablos and the Jackson Mets, thumbed out Diablos' park announcer Paul Strelzin for playing the song "When Will I Be Loved?" on the P.A. system after a disputed call.
The tune begins "I've been cheated . . . been mistreated . . ."

   Most-Remarkable Editing Catch -- Macmillan Publishing Co. deleted the name of Lou Proctor from its latest edition of The Baseball Encyclopedia.
Since 1912, baseball records have included a one-game appearance by Proctor for the St. Louis Browns against the Cleveland Indians that showed him to have walked in his only plate appearance.
Proctor's name was yanked after Macmillan found he was a Western Union telegrapher who'd inserted it in a box score as a prank.

   Most-Remarkable Performance by the Fans -- Milwaukee's Paul Molitor was elected to play second base on the American League all-star team even though he hadn't played the position all season.

   Most-Remarkable Promotion -- The Pittsburgh Pirates, hyping a three-game home series against the Mets in June, ran radio ads calling the Mets "one more thing to hate about New York."

   Most-Remarkable Performance by a Team Executive -- Chub Feeney, president of the San Diego Padres, resigned a day after making an obscene gesture at fans who taunted him during a Sept. 24 game against Houston.
The game had been designated "Fan Appreciation Night."

   Most-Remarkable Quotes -- St. Louis Cardinals manager Whitey Herzog on player-salary arbitration: "The great part is when it's over and the arbitrator asks you what a 'save' is."

   Ex-Yankee slugger Mickey Mantle on Canseco's "40-40" record: "If I'd have known it was going to be a big deal, I'd have done it myself."

</TEXT>
