<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS: Negro League Ball Players Feted </HL>
<AUTHOR> Rick Wartzman </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<DATELINE> Pittsburgh  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Between servings of roast beef and a cherry-topped chocolate sundae, James "Cool Papa" Bell begins, ever so slightly, to lose his cool.

   So rare for him is this moment of anger that his daughter cries out, "Uh huh, Papa, tell it like it is."
And several at this reunion of Negro Leagues players gather around the fastest man ever to circle the bases.
He inserts his dentures before he speaks.

   "They say we was born too soon, but it wasn't that," the 85-year-old says, bent slightly forward and peering through thick lenses.
"They opened the doors too late."

   In fact, by the time Jackie Robinson broke through baseball's color line in 1947, Cool Papa Bell's legs had given out.
He never played in the Major Leagues.

   At least not in the white Major Leagues.
For three decades, until he retired in 1946, Cool Papa patrolled the outfields of black baseball for the St. Louis Stars, Detroit Wolves, Chicago American Giants and Pittsburgh's Homestead Grays.
He hit like a hammer and ran like a cat.
Satchel Paige, the extraordinary pitcher for the Kansas City Monarchs, once said of Cool Papa's fleetness: He "hit a line drive right past my ear.
I turned around and saw the ball hit his ass sliding into second."

   Last weekend, Cool Papa was honored for his achievements.
He and a handful of other players from the Negro Leagues came here to Three Rivers Stadium, where they were praised on the field and, later, in a banquet room high above it.
Most of the men were part of the 1948 Grays -- the last Negro Leagues World Series champions.
For the record, they took that final series four games to one from the Birmingham Black Barons, which featured a 17-year-old slugger named Willie Mays.

   The Pittsburgh Pirates gave them bronze medallions and a hearty dinner.
Eloquent speakers told of their greatness.
As far as anyone could remember, this was only the second time that a big league team had officially remembered the Negro Leagues.

   Yet the Pirates are the first to concede that a meal can't make up for an eon of injustice.
Behind all of the happiness that the banquet brought, it generated considerable sadness, too.
"It's almost as if the records before 1947 shouldn't exist," says Clarence Bruce, the Grays' second baseman.

   Actually, few Negro Leaguers say they're bitter, or even disappointed.
Most of them are humble and gracious and realize, in the words of the Grays' nonpareil first baseman, Walter "Buck" Leonard, "they just weren't ready for us to integrate with white boys."

   In many respects, their lives were as good as they could be for black Americans of their day.
"They didn't think about going to the Major Leagues," says Phil Dixon, a Negro Leagues historian, "because they couldn't even get in the bathroom in most places."

   They've always been proud of the extraordinary things they could do on the field.
Every year from 1937 through 1945, the Grays won the pennant.
In exhibition games, they regularly defeated white teams.
Several Grays, including Cool Papa, have been inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y.

   To their communities, especially to a cold steel town such as Pittsburgh, these men "brought pride with their stunning abilities," says local historian Rob Ruck.
They traveled to Latin America -- where they were permitted to play on the same teams as white men -- and barnstormed across the U.S. Sometimes, they'd play three games in a day.
No matter where they went, they carried themselves with dignity.

   Some were lucky and, like Willie Mays, eventually found their way to the Majors.
Indeed, nine of the 11 men voted the National League's most valuable player between 1949 and 1959 were former Negro Leaguers, including Roy Campanella, Hank Aaron and Ernie Banks.

   The ones who didn't make it could only look back and do their best to understand the prejudice.
Catcher Josh Gibson, maybe the most talented Gray of all, died at age 36, only months before Robinson broke in with the Dodgers.
"We put up with a lot because we enjoyed playing ball," says Bob Thurman, who batted .345 for the Grays in 1948.
"That's the bottom line."

   Still, for some, the bottom line is the bottom line.
And though no baseball player in the '30s or '40s made anything close to today's towering salaries, the players of the Negro Leagues, not surprisingly, were forced to work hardest for the least compensation.

   Because the Negro Leagues never developed a pension system, as the Major Leagues did shortly after World War II, many of its surviving players have been forced over the decades to live in poverty.
And while the Major Leagues have earmarked proceeds from annual benefit games to older players who missed out, Negro Leaguers have no such program.

   "They're the whipped and forgotten men of baseball," contends Connie Brooks, Cool Papa's daughter.
"They all say it's all right, that it can't be undone.
But it's not all right.
Society has reduced them to nothing."

   Today, though, at least somebody remembers.
Out near home plate, Pirates president Carl Barger asks the crowd "to reflect upon the splendid contributions that the Negro Leagues made . . . to baseball history."
Men, once so lithe, hobble forward.
Buck Leonard uses a cane.
Cool Papa needs someone to support him.
The Grays, almost without exception, turned gray long ago.

   "We cannot make up the opportunities that were missed," Mr. Barger says.

   Vendors, oblivious, move through the bleachers and sell Iron City beer.
On the Astroturf, the Pirates and the Philadelphia Phillies stretch.
Players -- some black, some white -- toss the ball and sprint side by side in the green of the outfield.

   Overhead, the championship flag of the 1948 Homestead Grays snaps in the breeze, right under Old Glory.

   ---
   Mr. Wartzman is a reporter in the Journal's Pittsburgh bureau.

