   Last winter, baseball teams spent more than ever for
players. This summer, baseball fans can spend more than ever
to watch them.
   The average cost of a big-league ticket is 9% higher this
season, which opens today, and a family of four will drop an
average of $76 on a visit to the ballpark, according to a
survey by Team Marketing Report, a sports-business newsletter
in Chicago.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   That may be not only dismaying for fans, but also
disquieting for baseball, which has long tried to position
itself as the affordable sport. But, says Alan Friedman, the
newsletter's publisher, "somebody has to pay" for the
increases in salaries and other operating expenses.
   Baseball's lush broadcast deals with CBS and ESPN actually
do more to underwrite salaries than ticket sales. But gate
receipts remain an important revenue source which, unlike the
long-term TV contracts, can be increased from year to year as
costs rise.
   Team Marketing Report developed a fan cost index, or FCI,
measuring total ball-game outlays for a family of four. The
index includes tickets, beer and soft drinks, hot dogs,
parking, programs and souvenir caps. It has risen 72% since
1980, outstripping the 58% rise in the consumer price index.
This year's FCI is 6.3% higher than 1990's.
   Several teams have FCIs closing in on $100, including the
Toronto Blue Jays (US$93.29), the New York Mets ($87.40) and
the Boston Red Sox ($86.02). Toronto's 1990 FCI of $88.97
didn't keep the Blue Jays from setting a major-league
attendance record of 3.9 million, but baseball executives
admit price resistance is becoming an issue. "We're probably
flirting with that area right now," says Jim Ross, marketing
vice president of the Mets, whose advance sales have eased
from a year ago.
   Baseball executives say it isn't fair to hold most teams
accountable for all items in the index. Prices for such
things as food and parking are often set by stadium
authorities, concessionaires or other contractors. "Teams can
exercise strong input {on prices}, but they can't control
them," says Ernie Mullin, former senior vice president of
business with the Pittsburgh Pirates.
   Still, higher ticket prices account for most of the
increase in the 1991 FCI. Among the teams leading the leagues
in average ticket increases this year: the Detroit Tigers, up
15%; the San Francisco Giants, up 16%; the San Diego Padres,
up 18%, the California Angels, up 19%; and the Texas Rangers,
up 22%.
   "It's absolutely a reflection of the cost dynamics," says
John McMichael, the Rangers' vice president, business
operations. "Our last price increase was prior to 1988, and
our salaries have tripled since then." But there's been no
rebellion, Mr. McMichael says; in fact, season-ticket sales
are rising from last year. "The fans understand what's going
on," he says.
   The Chicago White Sox, cited by Team Marketing as having
the biggest rise, at 31%, dispute the finding. Rob Gallas,
the team's senior vice president of marketing, says Team
Marketing was wrong to include new $16 club seats, which the
White Sox didn't have last year and which aren't aimed at the
family market. Box seats rose $1.50, to $13, and reserved
seats rose $1, to $6, but Mr. Gallas says, "Let's keep this
in perspective. I went to the movies the other night, and it
cost me $6.50. Popcorn there runs $3 to $5. We've worked hard
to keep our prices in line."
   A half-dozen teams have held the line on ticket increases,
and Mr. Friedman predicts a number of others will step up
youth-oriented promotions to keep families coming in. And, he
notes, even some of the most costly teams offer bargains. The
Chicago Cubs, with an FCI of $83, offer upperdeck seats to
children for $4 (a 33% discount) at all games. The Mets admit
senior citizens for $1 at four games a year.
   Some teams are relative bargains all the time. The St.
Louis Cardinals finish in the cellar of the Fan Cost Index,
at $64.52, partly because the team, owned by Anheuser-Busch
Cos., has the cheapest beer, at $1.90 a cup. The Cleveland
Indians have the cheapest tickets, an average of $6.75.
   Even some teams whose payrolls have surged have kept fans'
costs in check. The Los Angeles Dodgers' payroll has jumped
65% since last season to $33 million, but the team raised
ticket prices only for box seats. "The competition for the
entertainment dollar is fairly fierce," says Barry
Stockhamer, the Dodgers' marketing vice president. "We think
our value has stood out, and we want it to continue to."
   The Dodgers will instead try to generate more revenue by
vastly expanding food facilities and menu choices (this
franchise does control concessions), opening a new stadium
store and, oh yes, winning. A contending team, it's hoped,
would get fan volume back up to the 3.5 million level of the
early-'80s salad days.
   There's nothing like performance to make pricing
considerations moot, agrees Texas's Mr. McMichael: "It's a
bargain if we win; it's overpriced if we lose."
