<DESCRIPT>  PAST; OAKLAND; BASEBALL; PROFESSIONAL; ARREST  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Former A's pitcher Mike Norris was arrested on suspicion of public
intoxication after a run-in with U.S. Customs authorities on Friday night but
was later released from custody without being cited.;    A spokesman for the
San Mateo County Jail said Saturday that Norris was held until deputies
decided he was sober and then released.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  NORRIS IS ARRESTED BUT ISN'T CITED  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Notebook  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Norris, 36, was arrested about 8:45 p.m. by San Francisco Airport police. A
police spokesman said Norris had caused a commotion by refusing to fill out
declaration forms demanded by customs officials.;    Norris returned to major
league baseball last year after seven seasons. But he was sent to Triple-A
Tacoma at midseason and suffered a rib injury in August. Earlier this month
Norris had said he was hoping to sign a contract with the Class A Reno Silver
Sox.;    Norris, who won 22 games with the A's in 1986, has had a history of
drug problems that twice forced his suspension from baseball.;  ANGELS: Dave
Parker ended a 3-for-22 slump with a two-run homer and Kirk McCaskill pitched
six shutout innings as California broke Cleveland's seven-game winning streak,
beating the Indians 10-0 in Palm Springs.;  BREWERS: Pitcher Ted Higuera, who
has chosen rehabilitation over surgery for a torn rotator cuff, was put on the
15-day disabled list. The Brewers chose to put Higuera on the 15-day disabled
list retroactive to Friday rather than the 60-day disabled list because they
believe he will be able to pitch by midseason.;  CUBS: Chicago reportedly is
close to a deal that would send reliever Mitch Williams to Philadelphia. The
Phillies would send pitchers Chuck McElroy and Bob Scanlan to the Cubs for
Williams and a minor leaguer. Williams apparently wants to be moved because of
his demotion from No. 1 stopper to No. 3 behind Dave Smith and Paul
Assenmacher.;  EXPOS: Former Giant Mike Aldrete, an infielder-outfielder, was
waived.;  PADRES: Pitcher Calvin Schiraldi was placed on waivers for the
purpose of giving him his unconditional release. Schiraldi was scheduled to be
paid $740,000 this year. Instead, he will get about $185,000 from the Padres.;
 PHILLIES: After allowing 11 hits and five runs in seven innings in a 10-1
loss to St. Louis, Terry Mulholland was named Philadelphia's opening-day
starter.;  PIRATES: Pittsburgh won't rush into trading All-Star outfielder
Bobby Bonilla and may keep him all season rather than deal for lesser-quality
talent, General Manager Larry Doughty said.;    A day after team President
Carl Barger said contract negotiations with Bonilla were at an impasse and a
trade was possible, Doughty said it would be a mistake for a pennant contender
such as the Pirates to deal in haste.;    "We're not going to give Bobby
Bonilla away," Doughty said.;    Bonilla rejected the Pirates' four-year, $16
million contract offer last week and asked for a five-year deal at "market
value.";    The Pirates waived pitcher Jay Tibbs for the purpose of giving him
his unconditional release.;  TIGERS: Andy Allanson, a catcher who spent last
year in the minor leagues, was acquired by Detroit in a trade with Kansas City
and placed on the Tigers' major league roster. The Royals received minor
league catcher Jim Baxter, who played only 13 games last year at the Double-A
level before a shoulder injury cut short his season.;  ETC.: Two American
League general managers said Pete Incaviglia may be claimed on waivers.
Atlanta, San Diego and the New York Yankees were mentioned as the leading
candidates. The Texas Rangers tried to trade Incaviglia to those teams before
releasing him Friday. If Incaviglia clears waivers, he will become a free
agent, and Houston and Seattle officials indicated their clubs would talk with
him then. Seattle is tempted to claim Incaviglia, a league official said, but
cannot handle his full salary. The Mariners tried to trade for Incaviglia in
the off-season.  </TEXT>
