<DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; BASEBALL; CLUB; EMPLOYMENT; TRAINING; PROGRAM  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  In 1985, the Pittsburgh Pirates had the worst record in baseball and the
club's worst record in 30 years. But the next season began with hope. The
Pirates had a new general manager, Syd Thrift, a new manager, Jim Leyland, and
a new philosophy.;    "It's my belief that if you really want to build this
ballclub into a championship club, it has to come from your scouting and
player development," said Thrift.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Special Section  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BASEBALL SPENDS A BUNDLE ON CULTIVATING TALENT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  BASEBALL '91  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The club employed 55 first-year professionals in 1986 -- standouts from
major colleges, junior colleges and high schools.;    In 1990, the Pirates won
the National League East. How many from the class of 1986 were on the
championship roster? Two, a part-time infielder, Jeff King, and a relief
pitcher, Stan Belinda. Three others -- Scott Ruskin, Rick Reed and Moises Alou
-- made contributions.;    By industry standards, the Pirates' class of 1986
was a success. The National Association of Pro Baseball Leagues estimates 8
percent of prospects signed "will make it to the major leagues at one time or
another," said Larry Wiederecht.;    Chet Montgomery, first-year minor-league
director for the Pirates, said "If 5 percent of the players you sign make it,
you've done a good job.";    Nine percent of the Pirates' class of 1986 made
it. The Pirates spent millions to develop a handful of players and their
effort was considered successful.;    Baseball's player development system is
beginning to draw scrutiny. Player salaries and related costs are soaring. Can
clubs afford to spend millions on a development system populated mostly by
players who never will play major-league baseball? Can clubs continue to fund
six to eight farm teams when the payoff is two or three big-league players a
year?;    The Pirates spent $6.8 million in 1990 to develop 216 players.
That's an average investment of $31,481 per player. If 8 percent (17 players)
eventually make it to the major leagues, the Pirates will have spent $6.2
million on 199 players who won't help them except in trades.;    As the 1991
season begins, few teams have made cuts in development programs. No clubs have
eliminated farm teams. The Expos added a Class A team.;    "Putting money into
player development is the right way to go,' said Bob Quinn, general manager of
the Cincinnati Reds. "Look at the nucleus of our championship club. Joe
Oliver, our catcher, came up through our system. Pitchers Tom Browning, Jack
Armstrong, Rob Dibble and Scott Scudder came from our system. In our infield,
(Chris) Sabo and (Barry) Larkin came up from our system. So did outfielders
Eric Davis and Paul O'Neill.  </TEXT>
