<LEADPARA>  Dale Long, who set a major league record with home runs in eight consecutive
games in 1956, died Sunday after a long bout with cancer. He was 64.;    Long
spent 11 years in the major leagues with the Pittsburgh Pirates, Chicago Cubs,
Washington Senators and New York Yankees.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  EX-PIRATE LONG DIES OF CANCER AT 64  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Sports Digest
Mercury News Staff Writer Pedro Gomez contributed to this report.
Last paragraph ran only in PM editions.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     His record string of homers began in Pittsburgh on May 19, 1956, off Jim
Davis of the Cubs. It ended May 28 with his eighth homer, off Carl Erskine of
the Brooklyn Dodgers. The record was tied by Don Mattingly of the Yankees in
1987.;    Long, as a member of the Pirates, was the National League's starting
first baseman in the 1956 All-Star Game.;  BASEBALL: Boston Red Sox pitcher
Roger Clemens appeared before American League President Bobby Brown in New
York in an effort to overturn his five-game suspension at the start of the
season. Clemens, given the suspension plus a $10,000 fine for allegedly making
derogatory comments to umpire Terry Cooney in Game 4 of the A.L. playoffs
against the A's, argued his case along with his agent and two representatives
of the Major League Players Association. Cooney and umpires' representatives
also attended the meeting, which lasted 5 1/2 hours. It was not clear when a
ruling would be issued. . . . The publishers of USA Today said they plan to
launch a weekly tabloid in April devoted exclusively to baseball. The weekly,
which will be called USA Today Baseball Weekly, will begin publication April 5
and have a cover price of $1. It also will be available by subscription for
about $35 a year.;  COLLEGE FOOTBALL: Fullerton State's football program,
which reportedly has been on the verge of being yanked from the university's
athletic budget, may get a reprieve. "I hear the program could be saved," said
a Titans assistant coach, who requested anonymity. "Something is supposed to
come down (today) that will save the team. If they are going to dismiss the
program, then it should happen quickly so these kids can catch on at other
schools." Because of financial problems, Fullerton State offered two of its
home games last season to the visitors in exchange for the $35,000 guaranteed
to visiting Big West teams. San Jose State, originally scheduled to play at
Fullerton State, snatched the opportunity for the extra home date. . . . A
21-year-old Maryland man who was in serious condition after a fall from a
third-floor window of a burning apartment building in Morgantown, W.Va., could
have been killed if West Virginia offensive lineman Ron Bunofsky wouldn't have
broken his fall, fire officials said. Bunofsky, who is 6-foot-4 and 255
pounds, said he was playing cards with his roommates across the street when
fire broke out at the residence of Ernest L. Wallace. "I was able to catch him
under the chest, and he landed on all fours," Bunofsky said.;  MISCELLANY:
Martina Navratilova played her first competitive tennis match in two months,
beating Gabriela Sabatini 6-3, 6-4 in an exhibition in Hong Kong. "It was much
better than I expected," said Navratilova, 34, who had knee surgery late last
year. "I thought I was feeling old, but my knees are good and now I feel 10
years younger.";  . . . The U.S. Soccer Federation and Adidas have agreed to a
new $21 million, four-year sponsorship contract that calls for increased
advertising and support by the shoe company.  </TEXT>
