   NEW YORK -- CBS Inc. delayed its third-quarter earnings
report until after the World Series, in a highly unusual move
that foreshadows additional losses beyond the $275 million
pretax deficit the company has already taken on its
billion-dollar baseball contract.
   The broadcasting company said third-quarter earnings,
which should have been disclosed yesterday, will be reported
in November after the completion of an "evaluation of the
carrying values of certain of its major sports rights
properties." Late last year, CBS took pretax losses estimated
at $275 million, and an after-tax loss of $170 million, to
write down the value of the company's $1.06 billion,
four-year baseball pact to reflect its depressed value.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The delay came one day after CBS garnered the lowest
ratings in broadcast history for a Major League Baseball
playoff game. Tuesday's opening contest of the American
League championship playoff between the Minnesota Twins and
the Toronto Blue Jays finished in third place behind the ABC
and NBC networks. The game on CBS was watched by 11.6% of
homes with TV sets. That was lower than last year's opening
National League playoff game, which at the time was the
worstrated championship game ever aired. That contest,
between the Pittsburgh Pirates and Cincinnati Reds, was
watched on CBS by 12.2% of homes.
   Tuesday night, by contrast, Capital Cities/ABC Inc.'s ABC
network grabbed a 16.7% rating, and General Electric Co.'s
NBC network beat CBS with a rating of 14.4% of U.S. homes.
   Many in broadcasting and along Madison Avenue argued that
CBS, then mired in last place in prime-time ratings and
desperate for a boost, vastly overpaid when it signed the
Major League Baseball deal, now in its second season. The
network was hurt further by the severe downturn in ad
spending and a glut in sports programming, which has forced
CBS to sell commercials for the baseball playoffs at rates
lower than in last year's games.
   But CBS had hoped the baseball losses were done with after
taking its large writeoff in last year's fourth quarter. Even
then, the network warned that it would run a loss for all of
1991.
   Now, "It appears CBS doesn't think their initial
write-down on baseball was adequate," said Lisbeth Barron, an
analyst with S.G. Warburg &amp; Co. "It doesn't look good" for
CBS, which has leap-frogged from last place to first in the
three-week-old 1991-92 television season. The rejuvenated
prime-time programming won't help the network's woeful
position in its baseball contract.
   "It's difficult to know how much of this is related to the
poor advertising environment and how much is related to the
fact that CBS simply overspent," Ms. Barron said.
   The baseball playoffs picture will likely get bleaker.
Like the American League finals, the National League playoffs
are between two teams, the Pittsburgh Pirates and the Atlanta
Braves, that are in small television markets and aren't
expected to draw as big of an audience as, say, the No. 2
market Los Angeles Dodgers, which lost the chance to be in
the playoffs by one game.
   However, CBS got some good news when the Toronto Blue Jays
defeated the Minnesota Twins in the second game of the
seven-game series, giving each team one win. The longer a
playoff series goes, the better it is for the network because
excitement, and therefore, possibly, ratings build. The
American League playoffs will not be a four-game sweep by
either team.
   CBS made its announcement after the New York Stock
Exchange closed yesterday. In late trading yesterday, CBS was
down $1.50 at $152.25.
   CBS expects to announce the third-quarter results prior to
early November. A company spokesman said the internal study
of sports costs began "recently," but declined to be
specific. The study will be reviewed by CBS's outside
auditors of Coopers &amp; Lybrand.
</TEXT>
