<LEADPARA>  Bo Jackson will make his Chicago White Sox debut as designated hitter Monday
night against his old teammates, the Kansas City Royals.;   The White Sox made
that announcement after Saturday night's 10-5 victory over the Cleveland
Indians, and Jackson was ecstatic about returning to the big leagues as a
player.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  JACKSON TO RETURN MONDAY
GWYNN STILL OUT WITH KNEE PROBLEM  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Baseball Notes  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "I'm excited," said Jackson, whose hip was injured in an NFL playoff game
last season. "I'm excited to be back. Most people said I wouldn't play
baseball again.";   Jackson spent the last week testing his hip in six games
with White Sox minor league clubs. He met with trainer Herm Schneider, who
said, "From a medical standpoint, Bo's ready to play major league baseball
again. He's ready in terms of range, flexibility, strength, pain level and
frame of mind.";   Jackson said, "If I strike out four times, that's great,
because I'll be back on the field doing it.;   "I'll probably always walk with
a limp," Jackson said, "but I run better than I walk. So, expect to see me run
a lot."; INJECTIONS FOR GWYNN: Tony Gwynn's left knee was drained and he
received a cortisone shot, procedures that will keep the San Diego Padres
outfielder out of action for at least two more games.;   Dr. Jan Fronek
drained fluid from Gwynn's knee, which has been bothering him since he hurt it
sliding during a game at Houston earlier this month.;   Manager Greg Riddoch,
concerned with the way Gwynn was hobbling to first base, removed the right
fielder after the seventh inning of Friday's game against Pittsburgh.;   After
two days, Gwynn's condition and availability will be evaluated on a day-to-day
basis.;   Saturday's game was only the second Gwynn had missed this season.
After Saturday night's games, Gwynn was leading the National League in
batting, at .323.; ETC.: Pittsburgh Pirates playoff and World Series tickets
will go on sale Tuesday by mail, the team said Saturday. If the Pirates win
the N.L. East, the first two playoff games will be at Three Rivers Stadium.
Games 6 and 7 also will be in Pittsburgh if necessary. If the Pirates play in
the World Series, Games 3 and 4 will be played in Pittsburgh, as will Game 5,
if necessary. . . . The California Angels have purchased the contract of
former New York Mets catcher Barry Lyons, whom the Angels signed as a free
agent June 19. Lyons hit .317 in 46 games with Triple-A Edmonton.  </TEXT>
