<LEADPARA>  First baseman Wally Joyner signed a one-year, $4.5 million contract with
Kansas City on Monday and repeatedly choked back tears as he discussed his
reasons for choosing not to re-sign with California as a free agent.;   "I am
absolutely thrilled to have an opportunity to play with the Kansas City
Royals," Joyner said in Miami Beach at baseball's winter meetings. "It was . .
. (20-second pause) probably the toughest decision I've made. I've enjoyed my
time with the California Angels. That's where Wally World started. . . . But
in my opinion, I didn't see a future with myself and the Angels.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ROYALS SIGN JOYNER FOR '92 AT $4.5 MILLION
ASSENMACHER-CUBS DEAL PAYS $7.5 MILLION  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Baseball Notebook; Mercury News wire services contributed to this report.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "My reaction this morning shows my frustration and disappointment that I
couldn't play for a great man like (Angels General Manager) Whitey Herzog. We
tried as best we could with what we had to go with, and it didn't happen.";
Joyner, 29, hit .301 with 21 homers and 96 RBIs last season, regaining the
form of his earlier years. He had reached an agreement regarding salary with
the Angels, but Herzog had said Sunday that the club withdrew an offer because
neither side could agree on "the payout of the contract." Herzog had seemed
bitter about Joyner's attitude in the negotiations.;   Royals General Manager
Herk Robinson said the club voluntarily waived its right to prohibit Joyner
from being a free agent for five more years.;   Joyner indicated the wholesome
environment of the Kansas City area was a key to his decision. "I have a
family that I care an awful lot about, and that was a real big reason I chose
Kansas City. I would like to stay there as long as I can."; CUBS KEEP
ASSENMACHER: The Chicago Cubs retained versatile left-handed pitcher Paul
Assenmacher by signing him to a three-year, $7.5 million contract.;
Assenmacher, 31 today, was 7-8 with 15 saves and a 3.24 ERA in 75 games last
season. He led National League relievers by pitching 102 2/3 innings.; ORIOLES
RETAIN OLSON: Gregg Olson, one of the best young relievers in baseball, was
rewarded with a two-year, $3.75 million contract by Baltimore. Olson, 25, was
4-6 with 31 saves and a 3.18 ERA last season. He set a team record with 37
saves in 1990.; BONDS TRADE AN OPTION: The Pittsburgh Pirates are willing to
trade outfielder Barry Bonds, but it will take a lot to get him, Pittsburgh
Manager Jim Leyland said.;   "We're not going to trade Barry Bonds just to
trade him," Leyland said while discussing the Pirates' options at the winter
meetings. "I'd rather play the 1992 season with Barry Bonds. I think this will
be a big season for him.";   Before the Pirates even got to the meetings,
Bobby Bonilla signed a five-year deal for $29 million with the New York Mets.
Now, they also face the loss of free agents Bob Walk, Mike LaValliere and
Steve Buechele.;   Last week, General Manager Larry Doughty said the club
would trade Bonds if it could not sign him to a contract extension. Bonds,
eligible for free agency after the 1992 season, will be seeking at least $6
million a season.; STATE OF THE GAME: Commissioner Fay Vincent issued his
state of the game speech at the winter meetings, telling baseball officials
that spending was out of control and suggesting a system of revenue sharing
needed to be examined. Vincent has said things like that in the past, and
often times they've gone unheeded.;   Vincent also issued a report on minority
hiring, saying there were more minorities working in baseball, but in the most
high-profile positions -- managers and general managers in the majors -- there
has been almost no progress.; EXPOS TRADE JONES: There was only one actual
deal involving major leaguers Monday. Montreal sent pitcher Barry Jones, who
had demanded a trade, to Philadelphia for young catcher Darrin Fletcher and
cash.; TOP D.H.: Chili Davis of the World Series champion Minnesota Twins was
named the outstanding designated hitter of 1991. Davis, who signed as a free
agent with the Twins last winter, hit .277 with 29 homers and 93 RBIs.;
Frank Thomas of the Chicago White Sox was second and Milwaukee's Paul Molitor
was third.  </TEXT>
