<DESCRIPT>  BASEBALL; PROFESSIONAL; OAKLAND; BEHAVIOR; HUMOR; LIST; OPINION  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  BEFORE he was great, Dave Henderson was fun. He has always been fun.;    The
gap-toothed smile, the standard pose. The way he squats to make a catch. The
way he stands after making a throw -- frozen in the outfield grass, his right
arm extended, the wrist gently twitching.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BASEBALL'S MERRY MEN  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Dave Henderson is so much fun to watch that he sometimes watches himself on
the scoreboard TV. He makes a great catch, he takes a bow. He waves to his
fans. He smiles. He prances. He dances. He hits a home run and minces around
the bases.;    Nobody in baseball has more fun playing than Dave Henderson.;
 It's not about loving to play. If that's all it was, we'd give you Cal Ripken
Jr., the man of a thousand nights in a row. It's not about playing hard, or
we'd be talking about Will Clark or Carney Lansford. It's not about being
exciting, like Ozzie Smith, or intense, like Kirk Gibson.;    It's all those
things and one thing more: joy.;    Dave Henderson plays the game with
unbridled, unabashed joy. He plays as if he just found out this morning that
he's in the major leagues. He plays the way you think you'd play.;    Only one
player in baseball comes close to matching Henderson's day-in, day-out
enthusiasm. His name is Ozzie Guillen and for the next four days at the
Coliseum, the Chicago White Sox shortstop and the A's center fielder will
provide a lively sideshow to the main event. The series opens tonight.;
Meanwhile, if you'll direct your attention to the third-base line, we'll
introduce the All-Fun Team. Enjoy the game. These guys do.; CATCHER: Boston's
Tony Pena works while sitting on his butt. He's a chatterbox, whether he's in
the clubhouse or behind the plate. "He always says how ugly I am, like I
should be wearing the mask," says Henderson.; THIRD BASE: George Brett, third
base? Sure. George Brett, fun? "He's one of the first guys I think of,"
Guillen said. So be it.; SECOND BASE: Jose Lind of the Pittsburgh Pirates. As
a hobby, he jumps over teammates while they're standing around the infield.;
SHORTSTOP: Ozzie Guillen. The camera pans the White Sox dugout and there's
Guillen, sitting on Carlton Fisk's lap like a baby. The evil eye, the voodoo
curse -- he's like the Chicken without the uniform.;    "I like to have fun. I
like to do crazy things," Guillen said. "So far, I've played for three
managers and they've all understood."; FIRST BASE: Joe Carter, Toronto.
Nominated by both Henderson and Guillen, he's an outfielder. But the outfield
is full.; OUTFIELD: Capt. Dave Henderson is joined by Seattle's Ken Griffey
Jr. and Minnesota's Kirby Puckett. Think of how many times you've seen Griffey
Jr. come off the field wearing that big, mouthy grin. Puckett just looks like
fun. Henderson agrees, but "I might have to drop Puck for Kruk." Puckett or
Philadelphia's John Kruk or Pittsburgh's Andy Van Slyke? We'll leave it to the
manager.; MANAGER: Tony La Russa, no way. Roger Craig, not now. Seattle's Jim
Lefebvre is so alive he's almost combustible, but the guy having the most fun
not playing this game is Tommy Lasorda.; STARTING PITCHER: Despite Henderson's
wishes for Larry Andersen, and at the risk of destroying team chemistry, the
choice is Pascual Perez. He pistol-shoots his strikeout victims and has been
known to make pickoff throws between his legs to first base. But the clincher
is that Perez occasionally does the "moonwalk" on his way off the field.;
RELIEF PITCHER: None. We're staying with Pascual all the way -- if he can find
the ballpark.  </TEXT>
