<LEADPARA>  IT WAS 1973, and San Diego had just drafted two-sport star Dave Winfield from
the University of Minnesota. Don Zimmer, then the Padres' manager, was
supposed to give the big outfielder a courtesy look before shipping him to the
minor leagues.;    "Right away I called (General Manager) Buzzie Bavasi,"
Zimmer recalls, "and I said, 'Let's keep him. He's better than what I got.' "  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HOT ROOKIE TAKES OVER HOT CORNER FOR CUBS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Some information in this report was obtained from writers in other cities.
N.L. Report  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Zimmer kept him, and it not only started Winfield's career quickly but
illustrated the manager's willingness to take chances on young talent. Zimmer
has showed that penchant from time to time, and the most recent example came
with his announcement last week that Gary Scott, 22, is the Chicago Cubs' new
third baseman.;    Scott, who has played only one full season of pro baseball,
hit .521 (21 for 41) in the first two weeks of exhibitions and showed good
instincts in the field. He will replace Luis Salazar, who will remain with the
team in a utility role. Third base had been the only large question mark for
the Cubs, who also added George Bell in left field, and Danny Jackson and Dave
Smith to their pitching staff.;    "I know there are certain managers who
don't like to play young players," Zimmer said. "I say give a guy a chance to
play. See what he can do.";    Two years ago, Zimmer insisted that young
catchers Joe Girardi and Rick Wrona could carry the Cubs through the stretch
drive of a pennant race. The Cubs won the National League East. If the
pitching holds up, Scott could be the missing piece in a World Series
contender. The third-base job was split last season among Salazar, Domingo
Ramos and Curtis Wilkerson.;    "I don't think (pressure) will bother him,"
Zimmer said of Scott. "He's just a good player with a good head on his
shoulders.";  BIG DEAL? While Bobby Bonilla was asking for $20 million over
five years from Pittsburgh, management was asking for a great deal itself.;
The Pirates, who could lose the outfielder to free agency after this season,
offered him to the New York Yankees for outfielder-first baseman Kevin Maas
and outfielder Roberto Kelly. The Pirates originally had asked for Maas and
two minor league prospects, but they felt that a proven outfielder also would
be needed in any such deal. Maas hit 21 homers in 79 games as a rookie last
season.;    "It'd be a good deal for the Pirates," said Bonilla, who was
raised in the Bronx, a mile from Yankee Stadium. He knows that if he was with
the Yankees, he would be at least a $4 million player. With the Pirates, he
tentatively will make $2.4 million this season, despite two consecutive losses
in salary arbitration.;    Bonilla, 28, hit .280 last season with 32 homers
and 120 RBIs, the most RBIs by a Pirates player since Willie Stargell drove in
125 runs in 1971.;    "I understand the economics," Bonilla said. "If I stay
in Pittsburgh I'll have a good year, and if I play somewhere else I'll have a
good year. I always give all I've got.";  NOBODY'S BUSINESS: Padres General
Manager Joe McIlvaine said he is concerned about the escalation of baseball
salaries, but he also is concerned about the public's knowledge of them.;
"The worst thing that happened to baseball was the publishing of salaries,"
McIlvaine said. "I'd like to see it as it used to be, when a man had his own
salary. All those human imperfections build on one another.";  PRIME POSITION:
When Atlanta left fielder Lonnie Smith underwent arthroscopic surgery on his
left knee Wednesday, it all but locked up the starting job for Deion Sanders.;
   Smith will miss up to three weeks of the season. Sanders, who came to camp
with a more low-key approach after being released by the Yankees, was hitting
.351 through Wednesday. He had scored a team-leading nine runs and had stolen
three bases.;    "We told him we would give him this opportunity when we
signed him," General Manager John Schuerholz said of Sanders, who had figured
to be playing at Triple-A Richmond. "But the guy has made us take notice.";
HAIL THE CHIEF: Earlier this spring, Commissioner Fay Vincent escaped a
hailstorm at Scottsdale Stadium by ducking into the A's dugout.;    "Hey,
Commissioner," a player told him, "this weather is terrible.";    "It really
is," Vincent agreed.;    Then, the player looked at him and said, "Hey, you
had an earthquake at the World Series, it rained at the (1990) All-Star Game,
and look at you today. Maybe it's you.";  NO TAKERS: Giants Manager Roger
Craig said he talked with Pittsburgh Manager Jim Leyland on Thursday in a
continuing effort to find recently waived outfielder Rick Leach a home. Craig
said the Pirates' recent acquisition of Gary Varsho from the Cubs left no such
room.;    "I think Leach will be a great rookie-league coach or manager --
when he's finished," Craig said. "He has so much enthusiasm. You can suggest
these things, but he thinks he still can play. And he can, if you find a team
that will give him a chance.";  AROUND THE HORN: For the curious, here is how
Barry Bonds and father Bobby compare 717 games into their respective careers:
Bobby leads in batting average, .275 to .265; home runs, 128-117; RBIs,
393-337; and steals, 181-167. Barry leads in walks, 377-321, and has struck
out 295 fewer times. . . . A Clark has led the National League in walks in
each of the past four seasons, Jack three times and Will once. Will leads N.L.
players in that category this spring. . . . Houston shortstop Rafael Ramirez
has had more errors than walks in each of his 11 major league seasons. . . .
Cincinnati pitcher Tom Browning has led the league in starts four of the past
five seasons. Robin Roberts, Don Drysdale and Phil Niekro are the only other
pitchers who have led the league in starts as many as four times since 1900.  </TEXT>
