<LEADPARA>  FIRST BASE -- Not a strength of either team. Gimpy Sid Bream will be a focal
point at the start because of his reluctant move from Pittsburgh as a free
agent after last season and his invaluable guidance for the Braves this
season. But Bream will give way for the three games after tonight to rookie
Brian Hunter (50 RBIs in only 271 at-bats), who bats against left-handers and
came through with big second-half hits. Pittsburgh also platoons with a
veteran against left-handers (Gary Redus, .143 vs. Atlanta in 1991) and a
rookie against right-handers (Orlando Merced, .333 vs. Atlanta). Edge: Even.;
  SECOND BASE -- Pittsburgh's Jose Lind had a big playoff homer last fall, and
he has been steady if not spectacular this season. Atlanta's Jeff Treadway hit
.320 in 306 at-bats this season, and he was 9 for 20 against the Pirates. But
Treadway has a sore wrist that will require winter surgery, so light-hitting
Mark Lemke starts instead. Edge: Pirates.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  N.L. POSITION-BY-POSITION MATCHUPS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     SHORTSTOP -- Jay Bell hit only .178 against Atlanta this season, but he
otherwise emerged for Pittsburgh as much more than the game's best sacrifice
bunter. Bell's 1990 backup, Rafael Belliard, went to Atlanta over the winter
and is basically a Jose Uribe who solidifies the defense but is an easy out.
Edge: Pirates.;   THIRD BASE -- This series will showcase the MVP favorites,
including Atlanta's Terry Pendleton. He played third with his usual aplomb and
came out of nowhere with his offense, winning the batting title with a .319
average. His leadership can't be overlooked, either. Pittsburgh acquired
former Stanford standout Steve Buechele from Texas in the second half, and no
one has a better glove at third. No. 6-hitting Buechele will force the Braves
to pitch to No. 5 hitter Barry Bonds, which is something the Braves didn't
have to worry about in the regular season. Edge: Braves.;   CATCHER --
Atlanta's Greg Olson made the All-Star team in 1990 and faded in the second
half; this season, he took over around midseason, when Mike Heath was injured,
and went on to become one of the team's top clutch hitters. Pittsburgh still
platoons Mike LaValliere against right-handed pitchers and Don Slaught against
left-handers, with success. Edge: Braves.;   LEFT FIELD -- Bonds for
Pittsburgh. Lonnie Smith for Atlanta. Edge: Pirates.;   CENTER FIELD --
Atlanta's Ron Gant was in the 30-30 club for the second consecutive season,
finishing with 32 homers, 34 steals and 105 RBIs. Pittsburgh's Andy Van Slyke
is the league's best at the position, and he hit .265 with 17 homers and 83
RBIs. Edge: Braves.;   RIGHT FIELD -- Atlanta's David Justice probably would
be in the MVP picture had he not been knocked out for two months in midseason
with a back ailment. He still finished with a .275 average, 21 homers and 87
RBIs. Justice is a better fielder than Pittsburgh's Bobby Bonilla (.302, 18
homers, 100 RBIs), but everyone in baseball is salivating over the Pirates'
slugger, who becomes a free agent when his season ends. Edge: Even.;
STARTING PITCHING -- Tonight's opener could be a matchup of back-to-back Cy
Young Award winners, with Pittsburgh's Doug Drabek the 1990 recipient and
Atlanta's Tom Glavine the leading candidate this year. Drabek was better than
Glavine in the second half and is hard to beat at Three Rivers Stadium;
Glavine was the All-Star starter and should be accustomed to the commotion.
Both staffs have three starters capable of dominating hitters (also Zane Smith
and John Smiley for Pittsburgh, and Steve Avery and John Smoltz for Atlanta).
Atlanta has the edge with the fourth starter: Charlie Leibrandt is in the
playoffs for his third team, and his six-game winning streak in the pennant
race was a major factor; Pittsburgh's Randy Tomlin had a 2.98 ERA in 27 starts
but was 8-7. Edge: Braves.;   RELIEF PITCHING -- Neither bullpen has a Lee
Smith-type hammer, although late-season pickup Alejandro Pena has converted
his last 11 save opportunities for the Braves. Pittsburgh's bullpen by
committee, featuring Stan Belinda, Bill Landrum and Roger Mason, somehow gets
it done. Edge: Even.;   MANAGERS -- Atlanta's Bobby Cox will win the
postseason award, not only for the team's mere presence in the playoffs but
for how he got the Braves through the midseason absences of Justice and Bream
as well as the late-season loss of Otis Nixon to a failed drug test. On the
other hand, Jim Leyland had to deal with the Bonds flap in spring training and
has been able to keep the Pirates focused amid constant economic issues. With
Whitey Herzog out of the league, Leyland probably is the best of today's N.L.
managers. Edge: Pirates.  </TEXT>
