<LEADPARA>  Andy Van Slyke does not consider himself "The Great White Hope" of the
Pittsburgh Pirates, but he did give them a great deal of hope Wednesday.;
Van Slyke homered and doubled to drive in the first two runs in a 5-1 victory
over Atlanta in the opening game of the National League playoffs. He was the
center of attention afterward because of that reason, and also because of a
race issue started a day earlier by teammate Barry Bonds.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  PIRATES THUMP BRAVES
VAN SLYKE'S HITTING IS A HIT WITH BONDS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  PIRATES 5, BRAVES 1; Highlight: Andy Van Slyke homered and doubled and drove
in two runs.; Atlanta (Steve Avery 18-8) at Pittsburgh (Zane Smith 16-10),
5:35 p.m. TV: CH5 CH46 Radio: KCBS (740).  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Bonds had called Van Slyke "The Great White Hope" during a discourse on the
Pirates' payroll problems. Van Slyke was signed last winter to a three-year,
$12.6 million contract. Bonds lost in arbitration, and teammate Bobby Bonilla
turned down a contract for the same average salary.;   When told that some
players who make $2 million are not worth that much, Bonds had said, "They
ain't black. And you guys know the truth. Everyone knows what's going on with
this team. Open your eyes. Wipe those glasses. You know what's going on. You
don't want to write it. You just want to goad Barry Bonds into saying it.";
Bonds then called Van Slyke "The Great White Hope" and added, "Do you think
Bobby Bonilla should make more than Andy Van Slyke? He's worth more. I think
so. But I'm happy for Andy. He's a great guy. He deserves it. That just means
I'll make more.";   After Wednesday's opener, Bonds said Van Slyke was the
"catalyst" for the team. When Van Slyke was told that, he said, "The way
Barry's been talking about me, I thought I was the catalytic converter.;   "I
realize what Barry's saying and it doesn't bother me," Van Slyke said. "He's
saying what he feels, and I don't really take it that way. I think he says it
tongue in cheek. On a baseball field, I would hope we're beyond the color
barriers of this game, and I believe we are.";   On the field Wednesday, Van
Slyke gave the Pirates just the start they were seeking. He homered off Cy
Young Award candidate Tom Glavine on a 3-and-2 breaking ball in the first
inning, and in his next at-bat followed a single by Jay Bell in the third
inning with an RBI double to right-center.;   Van Slyke has big problems
against most left-handed pitchers, but oddly enough, he is 13 for 35 (.371)
against Glavine in his career.;   "He just happens to be one of the
left-handers I do hit," Van Slyke said, "and because I do, I'm glad he pitches
for the Braves. . . . I think it was important for the club to get off to a
quick start, get the crowd into it and hopefully get the Braves' momentum
stopped a little.";   Van Slyke scored after his double when Bonilla singled
to left, helped by an awful throw from left fielder Lonnie Smith. The Braves
continued to look more like the old Braves than the new, blowing a big chance
in the fourth inning.;   Mark Lemke led off with a shot past first baseman
Gary Redus and could have settled for a double, but he chugged toward third.
Bonilla missed the cutoff man, but Lemke still was nailed at third on the
throw by Bell, the shortstop.;   "Getting Lemke at third was the play of the
game," Bonilla said. "If we don't get him, that may have let them back in the
game.";   The way Doug Drabek was pitching, all the Braves could hope for was
an injury that might knock him out. Which is what occurred in the sixth
inning, and even that didn't matter. Drabek doubled home Steve Buechele, but
was thrown out trying to stretch it into a triple. Drabek had to withdraw
after that because of either a bad cramp or a strained left hamstring, one of
which he said will be determined when he comes to the park today.;   The
Braves never seriously threatened, finally breaking up the shutout on David
Justice's ninth-inning homer off reliever Bob Walk.;   "It was the first time
for a lot of our guys, and I could see us being over-anxious," Justice said.
"But once we got to the third and the fourth inning, it was a regular game for
us.";   The problem was, it was over by then.; HOW THEY SCORED;   Pirates 1st
-- With two out, Van Slyke homered. Pirates 1, Braves 0.;   Pirates 3rd --
Bell singled. Van Slyke doubled, scoring Bell. Bonilla singled, scoring Van
