<LEADPARA>  Bobby Bonilla said Tuesday that there is a "99.9 percent chance" he will not
be back with the Pittsburgh Pirates next season. Barry Bonds said he would be
"right behind him.";   That is what it boils down to for the Pirates as they
meet the Atlanta Braves tonight in the opener of the National League playoffs.
The Pirates are in the unusual position of beginning a postseason with the
knowledge that there probably will be no chance of being back soon.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THIS COULD BE LAST HURRAH FOR PIRATES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  '91 Baseball Playoffs  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     There was so much talk of a "last hurrah" during Tuesday's workouts at
Three Rivers Stadium, it was as if this were to be the last run of "Gigi" or
the final concert by The Who. The Pirates are making only their second
consecutive playoff appearance, and yet the now-or-never mentality is
pervasive. Pittsburgh is a small market, and looking at today's baseball
economy, there seems virtually no chance the Pirates could re-sign Bonilla
and/or Bonds after this and the 1992 seasons, respectively.;   "Maybe a few
people might disagree, but all you have to do is take a look at the whole
situation," Bonilla said. "We're just going to do our thing. It's great for
baseball that Atlanta is in the playoffs, but we've got things to do.;   "It's
probably a 99.9 percent chance I ain't gonna be back here. . . . All you've
got to know is the history of the negotiations. I haven't really thought about
it much lately. It's in their basketball court now.";   Asked if this would be
a particularly emotional series for him, Bonilla said, "No. I'm looking
forward to playing many more, no matter where I'm at.";   Bonilla was given
what some would call a serious offer by the Pirates, four years for $16.8
million. But he and his agent are seeking a five-year contract worth $25
million or more, and they probably will find it. Both New York teams are
interested, and California has entered the picture. Whitey Herzog recently
took over as Angels director of player personnel, and he has promised to give
82-year-old owner Gene Autry a World Series title. Doug Danforth, the Pirates'
chairman of the board, has said he will make one last pitch at Bonilla, but he
conceded that the prospects of a return are unlikely.;   Bonilla hit a
career-high .302 with 18 homers and 100 RBIs this season. Bonds hit .292
behind him, with 25 homers and a career-high 116 RBIs, and with his all-around
game should have at least equal value when he becomes eligible for free agency
after the 1992 season.;   "If Bobby leaves, I'm right behind him," Bonds said,
"because that man has made this the best two years of my life. . . . I've been
here when we were sixth, when we made it up to second, when we dropped to
fifth, and now through two division titles, and I'm not going backward. If the
Pirates don't want to give us a chance, then I'm going to help someone else.";
  Bonds and Bonilla have another motivating factor besides the future, and
that is the past. They vanished in the last playoffs, a six-game loss to
Cincinnati. Bonilla hit .190 and Bonds .167. While Bonds said he "forgot about
it after we lost," Bonilla recalled some dominating pitchers.;   "Cincinnati
had (Norm) Charlton, (Rob) Dibble and (Randy) Myers," Bonilla said. "They were
outstanding. Not too many people were hitting them all year.";   The Braves'
bullpen poses no such threat, but these teams match up about as evenly as
possible. Atlanta won nine of the regular-season meetings, but those were
before: (a) Pittsburgh added Steve Buechele for protection behind No.
5-hitting Bonds in the order; and (b) Atlanta lost leadoff man Otis Nixon to a
drug-violation suspension.;   "We've got a game to win, and that's our focus,"
Braves third baseman Terry Pendleton said. "We've done that all year long. The
hype will be bigger, but we'll approach it the same way."  </TEXT>
